Welcome to my ✨ special ✨ repository! This file serves as a quick-reference cheat sheet for essential Git and GitHub commands.

🔄 The Basic Git Workflow

The standard cycle of working with a Git repository:
Clone ➔ Make Changes ➔ Add (Stage) ➔ Commit ➔ Push

Everyday Commands

Clone a remote repository to your local machine:
git clone <repository_link>
Check the status of your files:
git status
Stage changes (prepare them for a commit):
git add <file_name>  # Stage a specific file
git add .            # Stage all changed files
Commit your staged changes:
git commit -m "Your descriptive commit message here"
Upload local commits to the remote repository:
git push origin main
🚀 Initializing a New Local Repository
If you are starting a project on your computer first and want to push it to GitHub later, use these steps:

Initialize a new Git repository:
git init
Link your local repo to a remote GitHub repo:
git remote add origin <repository_link>
Verify the remote link:
git remote -v
Push your code (and set the upstream tracking):
git push -u origin main 
# Note: The '-u' flags means you can just type 'git push' in the future.
🌿 Branching
Branches allow you to work on new features safely without affecting the main codebase.

Check which branch you are currently on:
git branch
Create and switch to a new branch:
git checkout -b <NewBranchName>
Switch back to the main branch:
git checkout main
Rename the current branch (often used to rename ‘master’ to ‘main’):
git branch -M main
Delete an existing branch:
git checkout -d <BranchName>
🔀 Merging, PRs, and Forks
Merge a branch into your current branch:
git merge <BranchName>
Pull Request (PR): A request on GitHub to merge your branched code into the main repository. This is where code review happens!
Fork: Creating a “rough copy” or personal copy of someone else’s repository on your own GitHub account so you can experiment freely.
⚔️ Handling Merge Conflicts
A merge conflict happens when two branches have changed the same part of the same file, and Git doesn’t know which version to keep.

Steps to resolve a conflict:

Identify the conflicting files: Run git status. Conflicted files will be listed as “both modified”.

Open the file in your text editor: You will see Git’s conflict markers pointing out the differences.

<<<<<<< HEAD: Your current branch’s changes.
=======: The dividing line.
>>>>>>> <branch_name>: The incoming changes from the other branch.
Resolve it: Delete the conflict markers (<<<<<<<, =======, >>>>>>>) and edit the code to exactly how you want the final version to look.

Stage and Commit:

git add <resolved_file_name>
git commit -m "Resolved merge conflict in <file_name>"
↩️ Undoing Mistakes
If you accidentally staged a file (ran git add), but want to unstage it:

git reset <file_name>
If you made a commit and need to undo it (keeps your file changes):

git reset HEAD~1
To roll back to a specific commit from the past:

git log                 # First, find the commit's hash code
git reset <hash_code>   # Then, reset to that specific point
